## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### What breaks and why

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never triggers (no abort = no exception) |

**Pattern:** This is **timeout enforcement** — the correct replacement is `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` with `Task`-based execution.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation isn't instant** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, `CancellationToken` is *cooperative*. If `work` is a long blocking call (e.g., `Thread.Sleep`, synchronous I/O), it won't stop until it finishes. Pass the token into `work` if possible. |
| **Leaked `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer leaks. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at this top-level orchestration point. The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard distinguishes timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Fire-and-forget work** | After timeout, `Task.Run` keeps running in the background. The thread isn't killed — it just becomes unobserved. For truly uncooperative code, move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill`. |

### If `work` can cooperate (preferred)

Change the signature to accept a token so work actually stops:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        task.Wait(token);
        return task.Result;
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
    catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
    {
        throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
    }
}

// Callers check the token:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Async version (best for new code)

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

**Bottom line:** `Thread.Abort` was preemptive (runtime kills the thread). .NET 8 requires cooperative cancellation (code must check the token). The first overload is a drop-in replacement; the second overload with `CancellationToken` in the delegate is what you should migrate callers toward.
